Second lifecycle phase: starts the in-cage API proxy (billed modes only), execs the cage process via `bwrap`, and tears down the proxy once the cage exits. Entry point is `pub fn run_until_exit(r: &Resolved, prep: &Prep) -> Result<i32, CageError>`, which returns the cage's process exit code.

`start_proxy` binds a Unix socket at `prep.rundir.join(API_SOCK_NAME)`, spawns `proxy::serve` on a background thread with a shared `AtomicBool` stop flag, and uses passthrough auth — the caged claude's own OAuth header goes straight through, no API key injected (`ProxyConfig.api_key: None`). Only started when `mode_is_billed(&r.mode)` is true; `run_until_exit` sets the stop flag and joins the thread after `exec_cage` returns, regardless of exit status.

`exec_cage` builds a `BwrapConfig` (from `crate::bwrap`) pulling binds/env from `super::env`, then either runs on a PTY (`pty::run_on_pty`, interactive mode) or via plain `Command::new("bwrap")`. Interactive mode uses `setsid --ctty --wait` around `claude` so it gets a controlling TTY in its own PID namespace — omitting this makes Node's readline busy-spin at 100% CPU.

`cage_cmd_for_mode` dispatches per-`Mode`: `SelfTestStub` produces a containment self-check script (workspace writable, secrets masked-but-readable-as-empty, git functional, no network egress — writes confined to `target/` per ADR-027, cwd-relative per ADR-046); `Task`/`Interactive` produce the real `claude` invocation.

For billed modes, `claude_cmd` first launches an in-cage `socat` relay on `127.0.0.1:8080` (`RELAY_PORT`, must match `runtime::CAGE_BASE_URL` — drift breaks `ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL` wiring) forwarding to the bind-mounted proxy socket, then blocks via `wait_for_relay_snippet` until `/proc/net/tcp` shows a LISTEN row on that port (polls up to 5s) before exec'ing `claude`. This TCP-state poll is deliberate rather than a real connect-probe: `socat`'s `fork` option means any accepted connection — even an empty probe — gets forwarded into the host proxy, which would log spurious "EOF before request head" on every startup. The `mod pty` submodule (not shown here) supplies `run_on_pty`.